Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Figure 1.1. ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "P.wormer - Electromagnetic Wave - \
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Electromagnetic_wave.png \
- CC BY-SA 3.0"
}], "Affiliation",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8091805263102818`*^9, 3.809180554447837*^9}, {
  3.809183228593217*^9, 3.809183231040532*^9}, {3.8720044242695737`*^9, 
  3.8720044269054165`*^9}, {3.9142360650009403`*^9, 
  3.9142360664117002`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1039fa49-dd59-4138-8e39-\
59c2755ab13a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The speed of light was found to be a constant ",
 StyleBox["c",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (2.998 \[Times] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["10", "8"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "6754c4b5-eaf5-41f6-b86f-8d63206a1584"],
 " m ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["s",
     FontSlant->"Plain"], 
    RowBox[{"\[Minus]", "1"}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "14395e77-9ac4-4137-afba-9ecb996f04ba"],
 "), with the frequency \[Nu] and wavelength \[Lambda] of the electromagnetic \
wave related to the speed by the equation"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.914236609711622*^9, 3.914236618131432*^9}, {
  3.9142369027123923`*^9, 
  3.9142369927384295`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9e01c03f-a543-408c-a936-\
81924c69f3c7"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox["c",
   FontSlant->"Italic"], 
  StyleBox["=",
   FontSlant->"Plain"], "\[Nu]\[Lambda]"}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9142370167751865`*^9, 
  3.9142370438454037`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a25c689e-4435-46fc-a432-\
186413e80b78"],

Cell["\<\
In this wave-only picture, the energy of light was related to the amplitude \
of the wave, but this formulation alone wasn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t sufficient to \
explain some experimental results.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9142372988084483`*^9, 
  3.914237346261327*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f855f080-8338-4bc1-ba66-\
193e502483e2"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Ultraviolet Catastrophe", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.805647061526098*^9, 3.8056470915749197`*^9}, {
  3.8056471499966636`*^9, 3.8056471655717583`*^9}, {3.806340206562529*^9, 
  3.806340225536558*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5f2ee12e-5ee8-446d-98a8-\
a6972d005c1d"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A Blackbody", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8063402353821154`*^9, 
  3.8063402634955225`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e23750f6-1317-4b8c-a5d8-\
437909f52f99"],

Cell["\<\
By 1900, people realized there was a big problem with many  classical  \
theories. One of the prominent mysteries was the emission of light from a \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]blackbody\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]. A blackbody is an \
object that absorbs all radiation (light) incident on it (see Figure 1.2). \
They also emit thermal radiation (light) from the conversion of thermal \
energy into electromagnetic energy. The frequency of light emitted is \
dependent on the temperature of the blackbody. It was known from experiment \
that there was a maximum in the emission spectra that blue-shifted (decreased \
in wavelength) as the temperature increased. However, using classical \
mechanics (the Rayleigh-Jeans law), no maximum was predicted. Instead, \
spectral intensity was expected to increase with decreasing wavelength. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9142346555058193`*^9, 3.914234692656285*^9}, {
  3.9142350752396326`*^9, 3.914235127265959*^9}, {3.9142351619068303`*^9, 
  3.91423516394491*^9}, {3.9142352455407753`*^9, 3.914235263278256*^9}, {
  3.9142353024875526`*^9, 3.914235352974079*^9}, {3.9142353875488496`*^9, 
  3.9142353936723614`*^9}, {3.9142357291885977`*^9, 3.914235732689181*^9}, {
  3.91423607525021*^9, 
  3.9142360754622965`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0fba711b-c2c5-405e-bf63-\
98c9b069b00c"],

