Cell["\<\
Ok, so relating that back to de Broglie\[CloseCurlyQuote]s equation, we can \
now see that, for a matter wave,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8076212151944084`*^9, 3.807621241876628*^9}, {
  3.9142391966861515`*^9, 
  3.9142391973702335`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"80fafa1a-e9f1-4e2b-89a0-\
67d01446b976"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  StyleBox["p",
   FontSlant->"Italic"], 
  StyleBox["=",
   FontSlant->"Plain"], 
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox[
    StyleBox["h",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Lambda]"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox[
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["h",
        FontSlant->"Italic"], "\[Omega]"}]], 
     RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]"}]], "=", 
    "\[HBar]\[Omega]"}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8076212620444837`*^9, 
  3.8076213327245207`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4b332230-d797-436b-aaea-\
7e6a536b788d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where we are introducing the new constant (which shows up all the time) \
\[HBar] = ",
 StyleBox["h",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "/2\[Pi]. \n\nHow does this relate to the Fourier transform? Well, why don\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t we write our Fourier transform as a function of ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "/\[HBar] instead of just \[Omega] (these two quantities are equal through \
equation 28),"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.807621366793641*^9, 3.807621428727758*^9}, {
   3.8076216260639668`*^9, 3.807621741999625*^9}, {3.8076218104981775`*^9, 
   3.807621826816182*^9}, {3.809424598341811*^9, 3.809424611371684*^9}, 
   3.8094247214310493`*^9, {3.8094247610810614`*^9, 3.809424769278968*^9}, {
   3.9142392291490407`*^9, 3.914239244150196*^9}, {3.91423941623291*^9, 
   3.9142394191524124`*^9}, {3.9145996955407495`*^9, 
   3.9145996957459445`*^9}, {3.9339360224915695`*^9, 
   3.933936022655409*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"58f77f0a-fb9d-4ad0-8530-\
17205d7e8ab8"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["f",
    FontSlant->"Italic"], 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    StyleBox["p",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], ")"}]}], "=", 
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", 
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]\[HBar]"}]]], 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox["\[Integral]", 
     RowBox[{"\[Minus]", "\[Infinity]"}], "\[Infinity]"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["f",
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}],
      FontSlant->"Italic"], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      StyleBox["e",
       FontSlant->"Italic"], 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"\[Minus]", 
        StyleBox[
         RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", 
          StyleBox["px",
           FontSlant->"Italic"]}]]}], "/", "\[HBar]"}]], 
     StyleBox["dx",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]}]}]}]}]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8076217687493563`*^9, 3.8076217980122156`*^9}, {
   3.8076218361068153`*^9, 3.80762186512813*^9}, {3.809424615597525*^9, 
   3.8094246266335735`*^9}, {3.8094247728952913`*^9, 3.809424806987641*^9}, {
   3.8402729419353795`*^9, 3.840272945309718*^9}, 3.840273257789547*^9, {
   3.9144064697749133`*^9, 
   3.9144064708694386`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4dd39663-9b0a-4cca-bd2c-\
9bd2be9ef42f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Wow, did you see that? Now we can see, according to de Broglie\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s hypothesis, that there is a reciprocal relationship \
between ",
 StyleBox["position",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") and ",
 StyleBox["momentum",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "), and this relationship is in fact described by a Fourier transform!\n\n\
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s think about what that means for a minute. In our \
time/frequency example, the Fourier transform (which gave us a function of \
frequency) told the weights of",
 StyleBox[" frequencies ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "to sum up to generate the observed ",
 StyleBox["time",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " distribution. Now, we are talking about momentum/position, so the Fourier \
transform tells us the weights of ",
 StyleBox["momentum",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " values to sum up to get the ",
 StyleBox["position",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " distribution. \n\nWe can look at the demonstration of a function and its \
Fourier transform in Figure 1.10, thinking about position and momentum. You \
can see that ",
 StyleBox["if the position distribution widens, the momentum distribution \
gets narrower, and vice versa",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.807621903584357*^9, 3.80762196386865*^9}, {
   3.8076221381151776`*^9, 3.8076221383005843`*^9}, {3.8076229976511106`*^9, 
   3.8076229978732576`*^9}, {3.8076233517454605`*^9, 
   3.8076234178227324`*^9}, {3.8076240573899913`*^9, 3.807624214121138*^9}, 
   3.807624252755597*^9, {3.8076246658031816`*^9, 3.8076247146057577`*^9}, {
   3.8076247512152233`*^9, 3.8076248183480425`*^9}, {3.8402707759743204`*^9, 
   3.8402707853854294`*^9}, {3.914239441329378*^9, 3.9142394429481792`*^9}, {
   3.914239513579966*^9, 3.9142395261231775`*^9}, {3.9145996677687397`*^9, 
   3.914599668074007*^9}, {3.9339360512768517`*^9, 
   3.9339360516980305`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"29ac3023-8ed0-4df0-a7d2-\
0f31867ccc81"],

